  "diary": "Woke to grey skies and the steady drum of rain—perfect weather for staying tucked indoors, though I had to brave it to school anyway. The walk was quiet, film camera bumping gently in my bag. Classes felt a bit sluggish today; everyone seemed affected by the weather. I grabbed an ice cream at Molly Moon's during lunch, which felt indulgent and necessary. The afternoon chem quiz grading was tedious, but I found a few brilliant answers that reminded me why I do this. By the time I headed home, the rain had stopped and light was creeping back. That's when things picked up—met Maya at Pike Place with the market buzzing around us, grabbed some fresh herbs and caught up properly for the first time in weeks. Later, standing in my kitchen measuring out hops for the IPA batch, hands moving through the familiar motions, I felt that quiet satisfaction. There's something grounding about brewing.",
  "thought_process": "The grey morning put me in a reflective headspace, and honestly, the bridge closure barely registered since I walk everywhere anyway. I was tired through the teaching blocks—Tuesdays always feel like a slog—but lunch and that unexpected brightness after 2pm shifted my energy. I decided to prioritize seeing Maya because we've been overdue, and the market felt alive despite the weather. By evening, I was craving the tactile work of brewing; it's my real meditation, where my mind actually settles. The tea and journal time afterward felt earned. I think I needed today to be exactly this rhythm: structured work, genuine connection, then solo creative time. The world's chaos doesn't touch me much when I'm this grounded in routine.",
